Tukwila School District - Free Breakfast and Lunch

Due to a recent update from USDA, Tukwila School District will again be allowed to offer free breakfast and lunch to any person aged 18 and under, effective immediately.

Meals will be offered Monday through Friday from 10:00 a.m. to 12:15 p.m. at the following locations:

Thorndyke Elementary
Tukwila Elementary
Cascade View Elementary
Showalter Middle School

Only one breakfast and one lunch may be claimed per person per day.

In order to continue to keep our families and staff safe and healthy, masks will be required at all sites and screenings will be done upon entrance to meal serving sites.

www.tukwilaschools.org

Meal Services Changes

Starting September 2nd, breakfast and lunch will be offered to any student enrolled in Tukwila School district. Meals will be offered Monday through Friday from 10:00 a.m. to 12:15 p.m. at the following locations:

Cascade View Elementary
Thorndyke Elementary
Tukwila Elementary
Showalter Middle School

Only one breakfast and one lunch may be claimed per student per day. Please come prepared with the student’s name and lunch account number as this will help make the process smooth and efficient.

In order to continue to keep our families and staff safe and healthy, masks will be required at all sites and screenings will be done upon entrance to meal serving sites.

Free and reduced lunch applications are now available on our website at www.tukwilaschools.org. It is recommended that applications are completed and submitted to the District office as soon as possible for processing.

post_text:
From Superintendent Herndon:

Dear Families:

I had hoped to share a reopening plan that would have been able to allow all students back in schools in person this fall. We know that most would like to be in school and that our staff miss connecting with them in person as well. However, since the beginning of the COVID-19 Pandemic we have been working on plans that will allow us to open schools and to make decisions on instruction for our students based on what the science has been telling us about transmission of this particular virus. We have been monitoring reports of increased COVID-19 cases in our community and are in close communication with King County Public Health, OSPI, The Puget Sound ESD, and neighboring school districts. Based on the current trajectory of infections in King County. I will be recommending to the school board that Tukwila School District start the 2020-21 school year in a distance learning model.

Visit https://www.tukwilaschools.org/coronavirus-covid-19-information-and-resources/files/documents/FH%20Reopening%20Update%202020-07-23.pdf for the full text.

Throughout history sports have been used as a vehicle for advocating for civil rights. Sports provides a stage for all of the world to see and athletes like Colin Kaepernick, LeBron James, Mohammed Ali, Bill Russell, Jim Brown, Arthur Ashe, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Jesse Owens and many others have used their platform speak about the unjust treatment of black people in America.

In the wake of the murders of George Floyd, Ahmaud Arbery, and Breonna Taylor at the hands of the police, The Foster Athletics Department along with some of its coaches have chosen to use their platform to speak out against racism, hate, and injustice. The following images are posted in support of our community, our families, our students, and black people everywhere who face racism and injustice in this country.

Tukwila School District Book Sale: As a reminder, Tukwila will have a surplus book sale on the first allowable Monday after Tukwila moves to ‘Stay Home Stay Safe’ phase 2. Tukwila is scheduled to move to phase 2 on Sunday night (May 31), which means the book sale will be held on Monday (June 1). In the event that the ‘Stay at Home Stay Healthy’ proclamation remains at phase 1 the sale will again be postponed to the first allowable Monday. The surplus book sale will be open to the public from 9:00am to 11:00 am at the Foster High School PAC, 4242 S. 144th Street, Tukwila, WA 98168. In the event that the ‘Stay at Home Stay Healthy’ proclamation remains at phase 1 the sale will again be postponed to the first allowable Monday. The surplus book sale will be open to the public from 9:00am to 11:00 am at the Foster High School PAC, 4242 S. 144th Street, Tukwila, WA 98168. Only cash payment with exact change will be accepted and bring your own bag and face mask. The books are primarily old curriculum.

If you are interested in attending send an RSVP to woodardg@tukwila.wednet.edu with ‘Book Sale RSVP’ as the subject line to schedule a time slot to ensure social distancing.

On April 21st, State Superintendent Chris Reykdal, Office of Public Instruction (OSPI), released statewide recommendations and guidance on student grades for the 2019 – 2020 school year.

These recommendations came after careful consideration and included direct feedback from educators, students and parents. The recommendations require school districts to continue using grades to assess student learning and to support students by providing options to receive the best possible grade outcome for this school year.

Please click this link for detailed information: https://www.tukwilaschools.org/coronavirus-covid-19-information-and-resources/memos

post_text:
Message from the Superintendent's Office - Student Meal Support

Beginning Monday, March 16th through Friday, April 24th, the Tukwila School District will begin distributing free breakfast and lunch to all children aged 18 and under who live within our district boundaries. Eligible children must be present to receive meals.

Free breakfast and lunch will be distributed to all children aged 18 and under at any Tukwila School District bus stop at regularly scheduled morning pick up times, Monday through Friday. If you miss the bus delivery, please go to a Tukwila School District school for distribution of free breakfast and lunch between 10:00 a.m. and 12:00 p.m. Monday through Friday.

Please click this link for additional information: https://www.tukwilaschools.org/coronavirus-covid-19-information-and-resources

Next week, students will begin the second i-Ready diagnostic. Our partners at Curriculum Associates sent Plory, one of the main characters from the i-Ready program, to help "pump students up for success!"

As you know, education is a partnership between parents and schools. These scores are important because they gauge your child's abilities and inform the teacher what your child needs to know, or conversely what they shouldn't spend excessive time on.

You can maximize the benefit of your child's education by taking simple measures at home. Please visit: http://i-readycentral.com/familycenter/how-can-i-support-my-student/ for ideas on how to support your students.

Thank you for helping us to help your kids!

post_text: Members of the Tukwila Children’s Foundation Board (Riley Haggard, Mikhail Jackson, Mary Fertakis, Flip Herndon) paid a visit to each of the district’s schools in December to provide $500 grants to each building. The grants are to be used to address emergency student needs as they are identified by school staff. As part of the re-boot of the Foundation, the Board voted to renew these grants (which also include the Tukwila police and fire departments), which they have made in past years. The TCF Board encourages building staff to apply for grants for specific, unmet student needs through its online grant application form at:http://www.tukwilachildrensfoundation.org/

post_text:
This past Saturday was the annual Spirit of Giving Family Event, hosted by Parks and Recreation and made possible by generous individuals, businesses, and community organizations. Together, we served over 425 Tukwila children and their caregivers. Together, we collected gifts, experiences, and essential items with a grand value of $55,025! This accomplishment is the result of kindness coming together to serve the community we work in, play in, and call home.

On behalf of the Spirit of Giving team (aka Parks and Recreation staff), we thank you for helping to create a season of JOY and to lift some financial stress for Tukwila families.

GEAR UP Achievers Hosts First On-Campus Program!

GEAR UP (Gaining Early Awareness & Readiness for Undergraduate Programs) is part of a national effort to help students from low-income families prepare for and succeed in higher education. It begins serving students at the sixth or seventh grade level and follows them through their first year of college.

Click on this link for the full article: https://www.washington.edu/omad/2019/10/08/gear-up-achievers-hosts-first-campus-program/

post_text:
On behalf of the Tukwila Education Association and Tukwila School District:

The District is pleased to report that a tentative agreement was reached at about 1:50 a.m. on September 5th. Details of the agreement will not be released until the Association has an opportunity to ratify. Following Association ratification, the matter will come to the Tukwila School District Board of Directors. The District and Association are especially pleased that this agreement was reached in time to avoid any interruptions in the school calendar. Schools will operate on their normal schedule on Friday, September 6th.

#TBT More about those Cryptids! Ms. Fisher's 4th grade class at Tukwila Elementary School put together a "zoo" in their classroom for other students to visit. The 4th graders were teachers for
a day for everyone at Tukwila Elementary. They taught the kindergartners here about their Cryptids-- which are a mix of 2 or more animals sometimes from different environments-- and the student/teachers were responsible for explaining and sustaining them in the most logical way they could think of.

Congratulations! #ISpeakForTukwilaSchools

shared_text:
Tukwila Police Department
May 3, 2019 at 4:28 PM ·

Yesterday was our first ever Bulldog Bullyproof Training workshop led by School Resource Officer Tran with assistance from our Gracie Survival Tactics (GST) cadre leader Officer Richardson and our Records Specialist Lea Park who is also a jiu-jitsu instructor.

The purpose of the training was to provide students with basic non-violent techniques to counter common assaultive behavior displayed by bullies or others seeking to do them harm. Skills include verbal assertiveness and using leverage-based control holds to counter and neutralize threats without violence or use of punches, kicks or other strikes. The techniques are meant for the students to be able to gain control of an assailant in a non-violent manner until help arrives should verbal de-escalation techniques at the onset fail.

Thank you to the students who attended. We plan on hosting more of these workshops for students and hopefully for members of the community as well in the near future.

#graciebarra #10thplanetjiujitsu #gst

AN IMPORTANT MESSAGE FROM Foster High School (Tukwila, Washington):

A short time ago Foster High School was put into modified lockdown due to an armed suspect being pursued in the area around the school. Foster security, staff and administration acted quickly to secure the campus and ensure the safety of all persons on campus. The modified lockdown was lifted less than 10 minutes after it was put into place when Tukwila Police communicated that it was safe to do so. Thank you to Tukwila PD for the great communication and to our students and staff for following safety procedures and keeping all of our Bulldogs safe!

February 12, 2019 at 3:43 AM ·

For those wondering, yes it is possible to have quite the fire going even when it is snowing and with snow on the ground! A power line is done on the east side of the 14000 block of Interurban Ave S. Tukwila FD is on scene taking care of business and there are no injuries.

Photo Credit - Officer Watson
